Given an integer array nums, return an array answer such that answer[i] is equal to the product of all the elements of nums except nums[i].

The product of any prefix or suffix of nums is guaranteed to fit in a 32-bit integer.

You must write an algorithm that runs in O(n) time and without using the division operation.

 

Example 1:

Input: nums = [1,2,3,4]
Output: [24,12,8,6]
Example 2:

Input: nums = [-1,1,0,-3,3]
Output: [0,0,9,0,0]
 

Constraints:

2 <= nums.length <= 105
-30 <= nums[i] <= 30
The product of any prefix or suffix of nums is guaranteed to fit in a 32-bit integer.


class Solution {
    public int[] productExceptSelf(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;
        int[] output = new int[n];
        
        // Calculate lefts and store in output. It is left * nums[i] trying to get the most value of the left side of i
        int left = 1;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            left = left * nums[i];
            output[i] = left;
        }
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(output)+" output");
        
        // Calculate rights and the product from the end of the array. right will be the right most side of i and it will alway be product of nums
        int right = 1;
        for (int i = n - 1; i > 0; i--) {
            output[i] = right * output[i - 1];
            right *= nums[i]; // NOTE: taking nums and not the output. 
        }
        output[0] = right; // prev loop doesnt reach to the 0th index
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(output)+" output");
        return output;
    }
}
/*
left -> right
[1, 2, 6, 24] output
left = left *nums[i] // this is important

right -> left
[24, 12, 8, 6] output
output[i] = right * output[i-1] // important
right *= nums[i];
*/
